    <section id="realistic-earnings">
      <h2>4. What You Can Realistically Earn at $0</h2>
      <div class="table-scroll">
      <table>
        <tr><th>Method</th><th>Typical First-Month Range</th><th>Time to First Payment</th></tr>
        <tr><td>Microtasks / surveys</td><td>$50–$150</td><td>Days</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Freelance services</td><td>$100–$400</td><td>1–3 weeks</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Digital products</td><td>$0–$200 (highly variable)</td><td>2–6 weeks</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Affiliate marketing</td><td>$0–$150</td><td>4–12 weeks</td></tr>
      </table>
      </div>
      <p>These are realistic starting ranges, not ceilings — every method's income grows as you build a reputation, a returning client base, or an audience. Treat month one as a validation period, not a verdict on the method's long-term potential.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="red-flags">
      <h2>5. Scam Red Flags Most Guides Skip</h2>
      <p>This is the section most "make money online for free" guides either omit entirely or reduce to a single throwaway line. Anyone searching specifically for zero-cost methods is an above-average target for scams designed to look like one — the red flags below are worth reading in full, not skimming.</p>
      <div class="callout warn">
        <strong>The single clearest test:</strong> legitimate opportunities pay you for work or results. Scams ask you to pay first — for training, a "starter kit," certification, or platform access. If money is expected to flow from you before any work happens, treat it as disqualifying, not a minor concern.
      </div>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Guaranteed income promises.</strong> No legitimate method guarantees a specific dollar amount. Ranges and averages are honest; guarantees are not.</li>
        <li><strong>Payment required to "unlock" a free opportunity.</strong> A genuinely free method never charges you to access it, join it, or receive training for it.</li>
        <li><strong>Recruitment-first structures.</strong> If the primary way to earn is recruiting others rather than completing tasks, selling a product, or providing a service, that is a structural red flag independent of how it's marketed.</li>
        <li><strong>Vague descriptions of the actual work.</strong> Legitimate freelance gigs, microtasks, and affiliate programs describe specifically what you'll do. "Work from home, earn thousands" with no task description is a warning sign on its own.</li>
        <li><strong>Pressure to decide immediately.</strong> Countdown timers and "limited spots" language on a supposedly free opportunity are a manufactured urgency tactic, not a genuine scarcity.</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section id="next-steps">
      <h2>6. When to Consider Investing Later</h2>
      <p>Free methods are a real starting point, not a permanent ceiling. Once a method has produced its first genuine income — proof the underlying approach works for you specifically — a small, transparent investment in a tool or a training program can accelerate results meaningfully faster than staying at $0 indefinitely.</p>
      <p>The test for whether a paid next step is worth it is the same test that applies to the free stage: is the provider transparent about total cost, and does the price match what you're actually getting? A low-cost, clearly-priced training program is a reasonable next step once you've validated a method for free; a $0 "opportunity" that turns out to require ongoing payments is the same red flag from Section 5, just arriving later.</p>
    </section>

