    <section id="faq">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <details>
        <summary>Can you really make money online with literally no money?</summary>
        <p>Yes. Freelancing, microtasks, and affiliate marketing through free social platforms all require zero upfront cost — only time and an existing device. What changes with $0 is speed and ceiling, not whether it's possible: free methods generally take longer to produce income than approaches with even a small budget for tools or traffic.</p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>What's the fastest free way to start making money online?</summary>
        <p>Microtasks and paid surveys pay the fastest, often within days, though at low hourly rates. Freelancing on a platform like Fiverr or Upwork takes longer to land a first paying gig (often 1–3 weeks) but pays meaningfully more once you do.</p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>Is making money online mostly a scam?</summary>
        <p>Both legitimate opportunities and scams exist side by side, and beginners searching for zero-cost methods are an above-average target for the latter. The distinguishing test: legitimate opportunities pay you for work or results; scams ask you to pay first, for training, a starter kit, or platform access.</p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>What free tools do I need to get started?</summary>
        <p>A free freelancing profile (Fiverr, Upwork), a free design tool (Canva) if you're making digital products, and a free email or social platform account are enough to start. None of the zero-budget methods in this guide require paid software.</p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>How much can a beginner realistically earn with $0 invested?</summary>
        <p>Microtasks and surveys typically produce $50–$150/month with consistent daily effort. Freelancing income varies widely but commonly reaches $200–$800/month within the first few months for someone actively pitching. These are realistic starting ranges, not ceilings — income tends to grow as you build a reputation or client base.</p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>What are the biggest scam red flags to watch for?</summary>
        <p>Any request for payment before you start working, guaranteed-income promises, pressure to recruit others rather than sell a real product or service, and vague descriptions of what the work actually involves. Legitimate opportunities are specific about the work and never charge you to begin.</p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>Do I need a website or social media following to start?</summary>
        <p>No. Freelancing platforms, microtask sites, and affiliate programs all accept beginners with no existing audience or website. A following accelerates certain methods (like affiliate marketing) but is not a prerequisite for starting.</p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>When should I consider spending money on tools or training?</summary>
        <p>Once free methods prove the underlying skill or model works for you, a small, transparent investment (a paid tool, a low-cost training program) can accelerate results — but only after you've validated the approach for free, and only with a provider that's upfront about total cost.</p>
      </details>
    </section>

